## Strategic Concerns
The survey and analysis highlighted several strategic concerns critical to CareSplit’s product design and market positioning. 
Each concern is linked to actionable insights for the MVP.

1. Stated vs. Revealed Preference
Description:
Respondents’ stated preferences may not always reflect their actual behaviour when faced with financial decisions, especially regarding recurring payments and auto-debits.


Observation

Evidence
Implication for CareSplit
Users claim comfort with auto-debit
77.8% conditionally open to auto-debit
Trust is the key variable; adoption depends on transparent UX, consent controls, and predictable notifications
Low prior experience
88.9% have never used auto-debit before
Onboarding must educate users with visual walkthroughs before requesting authorization
Conditional acceptance
55.6% will adopt only if provider is trusted
Strong branding, credible partnerships, and clear feature communication are essential

Insight:
Conditional openness is not rejection. CareSplit’s Trust Architecture Layer converts these conditional users by combining education, 
transparency, and control.

2. Default Risk
Description:
The risk that users fail to complete scheduled payments due to insufficient funds, irregular income, or unforeseen events.
Risk Factor
Survey Evidence
Product Mitigation
Insufficient funds
33.3% cited as a concern
Implement grace periods, low-balance alerts, and one-tap reschedule options
Unexpected deductions
27.8% cited as a concern
Send 48-hour advance notifications before every deduction
Loss of control
16.7% cited as a concern
Provide pause, skip, or full schedule visibility at all times
Security/fraud concerns
11.1% cited as a concern
Utilize PCI-DSS infrastructure, 2FA, and NDPR-compliant data storage

Insight:
All default risk concerns are solvable design problems, not barriers. Addressing these in the MVP ensures high adoption and user trust.
Summary
Stated vs. revealed preference highlights the need for trust-building and user education before auto-debit adoption.
Default risk concerns are directly translatable into product features that prevent missed payments, enhance control, and ensure security.
By tackling these concerns, CareSplit can maximize both adoption and retention in a market with limited formal healthcare financing options.













 
